<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - ROCKER ARM ASSEMBLY, CAMSHAFT, TAPPETS AND PUSH RODS -
        ROCKER ARM ASSEMBLY - INSPECTION
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="5">
        <title>INSPECTION</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Visually inspect valve lever (rocker arm) shaft and rocker arm bushings for scoring or signs
                of excessive wear. If visibly damaged, replace shaft and/or valve lever (rocker arm), as required.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Valve levers have an oil spreader groove on the bushing. The oil spreader groove (0.011 in. -
                        0.018 in. {0.028-0.046 mm} depth), located opposite the oil hole, aids in oil dispersion over
                        the entire bushing surface. Refer to Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050508">5.8</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="ef1050506" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg12070" filename="../figcg1/CG12070.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.6.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1050507" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg2331" filename="../figeg2/EG2331.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.7.</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Retaining Ring</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Valve Lever</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. Bracket</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. Spring</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. Shaft</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1050508" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg2332" filename="../figeg2/EG2332.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.8.</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Part Number Location</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Oil Spreader Groove</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure valve lever bushings using a telescoping gauge and outside micrometer as shown in
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050509">5.9</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                . Measure bushings at two locations and record readings.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure the valve lever shaft with a micrometer. If more than 0.005 in. (0.13 mm) difference
                is found between the valve lever bushing I.D. and the valve lever shaft O.D., replace the valve lever
                and/or shaft; whichever part is worn.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If valve levers are within specifications, they may be reused. Prior to assembly, assure oil
                hole in valve levers and bushings is open by running a wire through oil hole. Remove any blockage before
                reassembly. Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050510">5.10</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
                <emph type="bold"></emph>
            </para>
            <figure id="ef1050509" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg3032" filename="../figeg3/EG3032.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.9.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1050510" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg12073" filename="../figcg1/CG12073.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5.10.</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect all valve lever shaft bracket orifices for blockage. Run a wire through each to
                assure they are open. Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk document="e105_86.xml" xrefid="ef1050511">5.11</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect rocker arm shaft springs as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect for rust, pitting and cracks. Replace as required.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Measure the spring tension using spring tester (
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE2241</emph>). Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk document="e105_86.xml" xrefid="ef1050512">5.12</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    and
                    <emph type="bold">"SPECIFICATIONS".</emph>
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Measure free length (no load applied).</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Apply correct test load and measure test length.</para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Replace rocker arm shaft springs which do not meet "
                <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS".</emph>
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
